  • Exports

Nim wrapper for WebUI

Example:

import webui

let window = newWindow() # Create a new Window
window.show("<html>Hello</html>") # Show the window with html content

wait() # Wait until the window gets closed

Imports

webui/bindings

Types

Browser = enum
  BrowserAny = 0, BrowserChrome = 1, BrowserFirefox = 2, BrowserEdge = 3,
  BrowserSafari = 4, BrowserChromium = 5, BrowserCustom = 99
CustomBrowser = ref object
  internalImpl: bindings.CustomBrowser

Event = ref object
  internalImpl: pointer
When you use bind(), your application will receive an event every time the user clicks on the specified HTML element. The event comes with the element_name, which is The HTML ID of the clicked element, for example, MyButton, MyInput.., The event also comes with the WebUI unique element ID & the unique window ID. 
JavascriptResult = ref object
  error*: bool
  length*: int
  data*: string

  RuntimeNone, RuntimeDeno, RuntimeNodeJs

proc multiAccess(winCore: WindowCore): bool {....raises: [], tags: [].}
proc multiAccess=(win: Window; status: bool) {....raises: [], tags: [].}

After the window is loaded, for safety, the used URL is not valid anymore, if someone else tries to access the URL WebUI will show an error.

multiAccess allows multi-user access to the same URL.

If status is true, then multiAccess will be enabled, otherwise, multiAccess will be disabled
